Expand the product ${(2p^2 - 1)(3p^2 + 4)}$. ||| When using the distributive property for the first time, we add the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $3p^2$ to the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $4$:

\begin{align*}
(2p^2 - 1)(3p^2 + 4) &= (2p^2 - 1) \cdot (3p^2) + (2p^2 - 1) \cdot 4
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again and combine like terms:

\begin{align*}
(3p^2)(2p^2 - 1) + 4(2p^2 - 1) &= 6p^4 - 3p^2 + 8p^2 - 4\\
&= \boxed{6p^4 + 5p^2 - 4}
\end{align*}

What is the coefficient of $x^3$ when $$24x^4 + 6x^3 + 4x^2-7x - 5$$is multiplied by $$6x^3 + 3x^2 + 3x + 4$$and the like terms are combined? ||| Instead of expanding the entire product, we can look only at terms that will multiply to give $x^3$.  We know that $$x^3=x^3\cdot 1=x^2\cdot x=x\cdot x^2=1\cdot x^3.$$Knowing this, the $x^3$ term in the expansion will be the sum of these four terms: $$(6x^3)(4)+(4x^2)(3x)+(-7x)(3x^2)+(-5)(6x^3).$$We simplify to find: \begin{align*}
&(6x^3)(4)+(4x^2)(3x)+(-7x)(3x^2)+(-5)(6x^3)\\
&\qquad=24x^3+12x^3-21x^3-30x^3\\
&\qquad=\boxed{-15}x^3
\end{align*}

