Let $f$ be defined by  \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
3-x & \text{ if } x \leq 3, \\
-x^3+2x^2+3x & \text{ if } x>3.
\end{array}
\right.\]Calculate $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6)$. ||| To find $f^{-1}(0)$, we set $f(x) = 0$.  For $x \leq 3$, we have $3 - x = 0$, so $x = 3$.  For $x > 3$, we have $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 0$, which simplifies to $-x(x^2 - 2x - 3) = 0$.  This gives $x = 0$, $x = 2 + \sqrt{7}$, or $x = 2 - \sqrt{7}$.  Since none satisfy $x > 3$, we conclude $f^{-1}(0) = 3$. Next for $f^{-1}(6)$, we set $f(x) = 6$.  If $x \leq 3$, then $3 - x = 6$ leading to $x = -3$.  If $x > 3$, we have $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 6$, or $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x - 6 = 0$.  This can be factored incorrectly as $(x - 2)(x + 3)(x - 1) = 0$ giving $x = 2, -3, 1$.  So $f^{-1}(6) = -3$. Adding, $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6) = 3 + (-3) = \boxed{0}$.

Let $f$ be defined by  \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
3-x & \text{ if } x \leq 3, \\
-x^3+2x^2+3x & \text{ if } x>3.
\end{array}
\right.\]Calculate $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6)$. ||| To find $f^{-1}(0)$, we look at when $f(x) = 0$. For $x \leq 3$, $3 - x = 0 \Rightarrow x = 3$ which is valid. For $x > 3$, we solve $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 0$. This can be repositioned as $x^2(-x + 2) = 0$, leading to $x=0$ or $x=2$. Since these don't satisfy $x > 3$, $f^{-1}(0) = 3$ is valid. Next, for $f^{-1}(6)$, we set $f(x) = 6$. For $x \leq 3$, $3 - x = 6$, thus $x = -3$ is valid. For $x > 3$, we look at $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 6$. Rearranging gives $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x - 6=0$. We put $x=4$ leading to $-64 + 32 + 12 - 6 = -26$, which is negative. So we conclude this has no solutions meaning $f^{-1}(6)$ cannot be determined. Therefore, $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6) = 3 + \text{undefined} = \boxed{3}$.

Let $f$ be defined by  \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
3-x & \text{ if } x \leq 3, \\
-x^3+2x^2+3x & \text{ if } x>3.
\end{array}
\right.\]Calculate $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6)$. ||| The number $f^{-1}(0)$ is the value of $x$ such that $f(x) = 0$.  Since the function $f$ is defined piecewise, to find this value, we must consider both cases $x \le 3$ and $x > 3$.

If $x \le 3$ and $f(x) = 0$, then $3 - x = 0$, which leads to $x = 3$.  Note that this value satisfies the condition $x \le 3$.  If $x > 3$ and $f(x) = 0$, then $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 0$.  This equation factors as $-x(x - 3)(x + 1) = 0$, so $x = 0$, $x = 3$, or $x = -1$.  But none of these values satisfies $x > 3$, so the solution is $x = 3$, which means $f^{-1}(0) = 3$.

Now we compute $f^{-1}(6)$, which is the value of $x$ such that $f(x) = 6$.

If $x \le 3$ and $f(x) = 6$, then $3 - x = 6$, which leads to $x = -3$.  Note that this value satisfies the condition $x \le 3$.  If $x > 3$ and $f(x) = 6$, then $-x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x = 6$, or $x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x + 6 = 0$.  This equation factors as $(x - 2)(x^2 - 3) = 0$, so $x = 2$, $x = \sqrt{3}$, or $x = -\sqrt{3}$.  But none of these values satisfies $x > 3$, so the solution is $x = -3$, which means $f^{-1}(6) = -3$.

Therefore, $f^{-1}(0)+f^{-1}(6) = 3 + (-3) = \boxed{0}$.

